{
  "texts": [
    "HYDTA approaches use control flow analysis to combine static and dynamic data, providing WCET estimates that consider both observed and unobserved paths.",
    "This hybrid method aims to balance the precision of static analysis with the realism of measurement-based data [38].Wenzel et al. [73] combine static program analysis with dynamic execution-time measurements.",
    "In the analysis phase, the source code is parsed, and static analysis extracts path information, which is used to partition the program into manageable segments.",
    "Test data is generated to ensure all paths within these segments are covered, using methods such as random vectors, heuristics, and bounded model checking.",
    "During the measurement phase, these test data force the program execution onto the required paths, with execution times captured by instrumented code."
  ]
}